00:00:03.470 --> 00:00:05.650
OTTO SCHARMER: So good
morning, everyone.

00:00:05.650 --> 00:00:11.780
I do feel this situation
has happened often

00:00:11.780 --> 00:00:16.620
to me because I am from MIT.

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:20.240
And I don't know how often we
do also these live, global, very

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:21.330
ambitious things.

00:00:21.330 --> 00:00:26.940
And you run into all the
fundamental problems.

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:28.720
And then, oh, what?

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:29.220
Really?

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:29.920
Is that true?

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:33.230
MIT, and you can't put
these two things together?

00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:36.340
So I have been in that
situation also quite often.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:45.740
So I want to share this
morning a few experiences

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:51.640
and stories around two guiding
questions that interest me

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:52.140
most.

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:58.380
One is how to use the power of
technology for good basically.

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:07.230
And as we all know, [INAUDIBLE]
and others from the Arab Spring

00:01:07.230 --> 00:01:11.980
revolution, and so on, there
is with many people a sense

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:14.920
that social media is
good at breaking things.

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:16.650
But is it also good
at making things?

00:01:16.650 --> 00:01:21.480
So that has been called into
question by social change

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:22.960
activists more recently.

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:26.450
So how to use technology
for good is one question.

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:31.180
And the other one is how to
use the power of mindfulness

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:37.520
not only for the cultivation
of the individual,

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:42.380
but also for the evolution
and transformation of larger

00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:44.450
systems, of the collective.

00:01:44.450 --> 00:01:46.720
So that's really
what's interesting me,

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:49.100
and the intersection
of these two questions.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:53.600
So I want to also introduce
my colleague and co-creator

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:56.370
of U.Lab at MIT and the
Presencing Institute Adam

00:01:56.370 --> 00:02:01.600
Yukelson, who on short
notice is in town

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:06.450
and is able to also join in
for the discussion later today.

00:02:06.450 --> 00:02:11.340
So I want to start off
with-- I know no one can

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:13.460
see it, but maybe some remote.

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:17.090
So it's basically--
oh, we have it here.

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:19.280
Wonderful, we have it here.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:23.460
So it's that kind of situation.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:26.890
I just find it interesting,
and I'm sure many of you

00:02:26.890 --> 00:02:28.370
have experienced that as well.

00:02:28.370 --> 00:02:32.560
You go to other countries,
you go to other systems

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:36.060
and communities,
this kind of feeling,

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:40.710
a feeling of disruptive
change is true on many levels

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:42.800
off scale today on
an individual level.

00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:45.590
Organizationally,
we face disruption.

00:02:45.590 --> 00:02:47.700
Certainly, here in Europe.

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:50.360
I mean, no one needs
to explain that.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:53.730
But also worldwide
with ecological

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:55.243
and social and other challenges.

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:00.750
So everyone is talking
about disruption.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:02.760
That's no longer anything new.

00:03:02.760 --> 00:03:07.650
What's the perspective we
take from the mindfulness,

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:11.360
or the term we
use is presencing.

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:13.890
And we mean by
presencing the capacity

00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:17.890
of sensing an actualizing
emerging future possibilities.

00:03:17.890 --> 00:03:21.660
So what's the
perspective we take?

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:24.120
The perspective we
take is that each

00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:28.440
of us in each human system
and social system today

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:32.040
is not only sitting on this
side, the current reality

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:35.910
side of disruption, but
one part of ourselves

00:03:35.910 --> 00:03:39.060
is also located here
on the other side,

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:41.710
in other words, which is kind
of representing the emerging

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:43.300
future.

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:45.440
In other words, we
operate on the assumption

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:48.170
that the future
is already there.

00:03:48.170 --> 00:03:52.810
We just need to learn how to
notice it and pay attention

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:53.310
to it.

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:56.750
Because it's usually
not inside our bubble.

00:03:56.750 --> 00:03:58.560
It's not in our main focus.

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:01.340
But it may be a
little left and right.

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:06.840
And that's a little bit
the topic I want to follow.

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:10.730
So the two ideas,
the two guiding ideas

00:04:10.730 --> 00:04:15.090
we use, the first one, I'm
sure you have seen many times.

00:04:15.090 --> 00:04:16.959
It's the iceberg model,
systems thinking.

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:18.260
10% is visible.

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:23.540
The other 90% also matters.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:27.650
And so it's like on the
surface, we have symptoms.

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:32.950
Then there is structures
and systems underneath.

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:36.850
So for example, if we look
at the current situation

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:40.320
in Europe, you could
say symptoms is Brexit,

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:44.330
a lot of people disenchanted
with the European project you

00:04:44.330 --> 00:04:45.020
could say.

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:47.370
Underneath, structures
and systems, a lot

00:04:47.370 --> 00:04:49.560
of systemic disconnects, right?

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:52.990
If you look at the map,
the vote-- when was it?

00:04:52.990 --> 00:04:54.810
Last week?

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:57.480
One way of interpreting
that is basically

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:00.470
representing inequity
in commitment

00:05:00.470 --> 00:05:01.900
to do something about it, right?

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:05.770
So it's kind of the long
term results of the Thatcher

00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:09.380
revolution that are
visible also in the votes.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:14.240
So many people having the
feeling that the systems--

00:05:14.240 --> 00:05:18.010
the bigger the system, the more
the mistrust and disappointment

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:22.930
because it's accumulated
in your life experience.

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:26.590
And we see similar patterns
in the rise of the Trump

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:30.300
phenomenon and the
rise of the right here

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.540
across all countries in
Europe, and similar phenomena

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:36.230
also in Asia.

00:05:36.230 --> 00:05:38.630
But then, what's underneath?

00:05:38.630 --> 00:05:39.410
What's driving?

00:05:39.410 --> 00:05:42.940
So there's a number of
systemic disconnects

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:47.200
that I could-- the disconnect
between, for example,

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:52.160
finite resources and the
infinite growth paradigm.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.140
So that's an obvious
one kind of related

00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:56.950
to the ecological crisis.

00:05:56.950 --> 00:06:00.880
But it's also a disconnect
between the real economy

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:05.430
and the financial economy when
there is something getting out

00:06:05.430 --> 00:06:06.370
of sync.

00:06:06.370 --> 00:06:13.920
And there is a disconnect,
also well-known,

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:16.200
between GDP and well-being.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:20.250
For all developed
countries, more GDP

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:22.010
does not translate
into more well-being.

00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:26.250
So it's no longer a good
measure for economic progress.

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:30.410
If it's not GDP, then what is
it, these kinds of questions.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:34.570
But if you go a little
deeper underneath,

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:38.970
the next deeper level of
root causes, I believe,

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:43.260
has to do particular
with root causes that

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:46.420
originate between our
ears, that originate

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:50.060
in our qualities of
thought, particularly

00:06:50.060 --> 00:06:54.410
the outdated paradigms
of economic thought

00:06:54.410 --> 00:06:57.470
that we still use and
teach at business schools

00:06:57.470 --> 00:07:00.460
and use to design economic
institutions based

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:01.890
on which way we operate.

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:06.950
So you can say thinking
creates the world in many ways.

00:07:06.950 --> 00:07:10.160
And what we see today, the
enacted economic reality,

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:13.650
is really an embodiment
of yesterday's paradigm

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:15.380
of economic thought.

00:07:15.380 --> 00:07:19.100
So when you look
at the evolution

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:23.900
of the economic thought and
the evolution of the economy,

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:27.010
you can see a movement
from centralized to free

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:30.720
market-- laissez-faire
capitalism-- to a more

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:36.440
social market economy like
20th century OECD countries.

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:39.540
And today, at the beginning
of the 21st century,

00:07:39.540 --> 00:07:43.440
we move from this 3.0 economy.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:46.650
We believe there's a possibility
of the current crisis

00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:51.250
to progress to a 4.0 economy
in which the three sectors--

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:54.820
business, governments,
and society-- no longer

00:07:54.820 --> 00:07:58.240
or just work against
each other, but begin

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:01.010
to work with each other
in order to innovate

00:08:01.010 --> 00:08:02.850
at the scale of
the whole system,

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:07.070
addressing some of these
bigger issues like inequity

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:10.370
or connected to the
ecological crisis.

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:14.480
So that's, you
could say, the basic

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:19.310
view that we have been taking.

00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:25.430
In other words, we see the
evolution of the modern economy

00:08:25.430 --> 00:08:30.810
based on distribution of labor
and the evolution of economic

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:34.570
thought as an embodiment of
human consciousness that moves

00:08:34.570 --> 00:08:37.500
from traditional
awareness-- like loyalty,

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:40.700
fitting in-- to
ego-system awareness,

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:43.100
which is what we still teach
at business schools today,

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:46.870
homo economicus, to
stakeholder awareness,

00:08:46.870 --> 00:08:50.120
which is what we use in all
real companies or governmental

00:08:50.120 --> 00:08:56.690
institutions today, to what we
believe will be foundation this

00:08:56.690 --> 00:08:59.630
century, which is
ecosystem awareness,

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:03.910
by which we mean an awareness
that's not only focusing

00:09:03.910 --> 00:09:06.440
on my well-being--
ego-system awareness--

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:10.950
or the well-being of the
few key stakeholders--

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:12.490
stakeholder awareness--

00:09:12.490 --> 00:09:16.370
but that's focusing on the
well-being of all partners

00:09:16.370 --> 00:09:20.420
in an ecosystem,
particularly those

00:09:20.420 --> 00:09:26.000
that are least connected
and most disadvantaged.

00:09:29.390 --> 00:09:32.310
The past 15 years,
I've done many projects

00:09:32.310 --> 00:09:37.870
in sustainability,
education, health, business.

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:41.090
And basically, in
all these situations,

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:45.510
you face the same basic
issue that to make progress,

00:09:45.510 --> 00:09:50.570
or the big challenges today,
no one can do it alone, right?

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:55.060
You need to bring together a
diverse group of stakeholders

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:57.960
that need each other
to make progress.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:00.220
And then, once you
get that, you need

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:05.100
to help them to move from
a silo type of viewpoint

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.930
and interaction, or
ego-system awareness,

00:10:07.930 --> 00:10:12.060
to ecosystem awareness, which
is a view that is more embedded

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:14.440
in the whole system view.

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:16.880
And that's basically
our bread and butter.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:19.550
I mean, that's what
we have been doing.

00:10:19.550 --> 00:10:26.660
And so let me quickly--
we developed basically

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:34.390
a method that is taking people
who want to engage on this ego

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:38.620
to ecosystem process, on a
journey that moves through

00:10:38.620 --> 00:10:42.240
observe, observe, seeing
the system from the edges,

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:45.170
deep reflexion, rapid cycle
prototyping, like design

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:51.970
thinking, but that also
invites people to basically do

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:55.310
some inner leadership
work, which is basically

00:10:55.310 --> 00:10:56.980
quality of listening.

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:01.840
So seeing your system
from different angles

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:03.700
doesn't help if
you still project

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:05.750
your old habits of judgment.

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:09.760
So the inner
leadership work that we

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:13.940
believe is necessary
today is basically

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:16.530
the development of
three inner instruments

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:21.280
of knowing that we call open
mind, open heart, open will.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:25.530
And open mind
really means suspend

00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:27.110
your old habits of thought.

00:11:27.110 --> 00:11:30.220
Look with fresh eyes
into a situation.

00:11:30.220 --> 00:11:33.650
Open heart really
means look at it.

00:11:33.650 --> 00:11:36.870
So develop the capacity
to look at a problem

00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:40.930
not from your angle, but from
the angle of your stakeholders,

00:11:40.930 --> 00:11:44.250
from the partners
you're working with.

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:47.970
In all network
leadership challenges,

00:11:47.970 --> 00:11:51.880
that's the number
one capacity that you

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:54.780
need to be effective in
situations like that.

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:57.700
And the third one, open will,
is basically the capacity

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:00.300
to let go and let come.

00:12:00.300 --> 00:12:03.480
That's the reason why usually
mergers don't work, right?

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:07.420
It's because we hold on to
the old definition of us

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:13.470
versus them, and thereby
block an evolution to a new

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:19.570
we or a new kind of evolution
to connect to the deeper

00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:22.600
sources of knowing.

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:25.660
So that's basically
what we have been doing.

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:28.280
There is a-- but I'm
not going into that

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:33.760
because as you can
see the pictures,

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:39.190
we have been using that
in a number of projects

00:12:39.190 --> 00:12:41.640
in public sector,
private sector.

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.540
The bottom line
is you can do it.

00:12:50.540 --> 00:12:51.480
It does work.

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:52.790
It takes a lot of effort.

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:59.970
But what are some
of the deeper shifts

00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:02.010
that you can observe there?

00:13:02.010 --> 00:13:03.490
And I think this
is a visible one.

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:06.950
So there's a little
summary slide here.

00:13:06.950 --> 00:13:12.910
What we notice, if
you take systems

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:15.390
through a journey-- kind
of where you move basically

00:13:15.390 --> 00:13:21.790
from the me to we shift--
where people begin across

00:13:21.790 --> 00:13:28.040
organization and sector
boundaries to communicate

00:13:28.040 --> 00:13:31.020
in a more fluid, in
a more direct way,

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:35.230
and therefore kind of develop
a more distributed intelligence

00:13:35.230 --> 00:13:37.840
that allows people to
co-sense kind of what

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:41.130
the current situation is
like and develop ideas

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.640
and explore them quickly
with experimentation.

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:49.080
The main shift that happens
is not only outcomes

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:52.895
that you create, for
example, reducing

00:13:52.895 --> 00:13:55.510
mortality and so forth.

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:58.710
But it's a mindset shift
that can be summarized

00:13:58.710 --> 00:13:59.800
with this picture here.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:02.000
It's a mindset
shift from this way

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.040
of seeing the
system as something

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:10.280
out there to seeing
the system that way,

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:16.120
which is a way that includes
myself as part of the picture.

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:19.180
So that's really at
the end of the day,

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:23.740
if you have a successful
process, that's

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:27.520
kind of the fundamental mindset
shift that, if in place,

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:30.450
allows you to be much
more effective in dealing

00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:31.570
with issues.

00:14:31.570 --> 00:14:35.950
And when you have a conflict
situation, a real conflict

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:39.500
situation, different
interest clashing,

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:44.480
to come up with productive
ways of dealing with that.

00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:48.860
And when you move from
this mindset, the realities

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:54.412
out there, to this mindset
as an individual, what

00:14:54.412 --> 00:14:55.120
do you call that?

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:56.480
What's the word for that?

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:59.930
What's the English word
that we use for that shift?

00:14:59.930 --> 00:15:04.136
What do we call-- how do
we label the second state?

00:15:04.136 --> 00:15:06.035
SPEAKER 1: It's
a transformation.

00:15:06.035 --> 00:15:07.160
OTTO SCHARMER: What's that?

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:08.230
SPEAKER 1: It's
a transformation.

00:15:08.230 --> 00:15:10.396
OTTO SCHARMER: Transformation,
yeah, transformation.

00:15:10.396 --> 00:15:11.650
What other words for that?

00:15:11.650 --> 00:15:12.400
AUDIENCE: Empathy.

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:18.570
OTTO SCHARMER:
Yeah, well, in a way

00:15:18.570 --> 00:15:22.780
you could say it's like seeing
yourself as part of the system.

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:26.550
Often like there is empathy
with others, empathy with self.

00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:28.690
Yeah, that's connected to that.

00:15:28.690 --> 00:15:34.290
I think a lot has to do
with the term mindfulness.

00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:40.050
And if you look at the field of
leadership, which is my field,

00:15:40.050 --> 00:15:42.520
and you know like
I know everything

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:45.430
has been said too often by
too many people already.

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:47.820
So what is really new?

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:52.810
Very little things when you
look at the whole field.

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:56.520
But one of the things I
think that truly is new,

00:15:56.520 --> 00:16:03.510
let's say the past 10, 15 years,
is the rise of mindfulness

00:16:03.510 --> 00:16:07.240
from being a very marginal
term 10, 15 years ago

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:11.070
to being very central,
almost mainstream,

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:12.340
in four different areas.

00:16:12.340 --> 00:16:18.380
It's in our cognition science,
health and well-being,

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:21.360
education, the whole movement
around social-emotional

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:23.830
learning, and now
the fourth one,

00:16:23.830 --> 00:16:28.680
as you can see in [? Davos ?]
and other places-- leadership.

00:16:28.680 --> 00:16:33.630
And why is it more than
maybe a personal interest?

00:16:33.630 --> 00:16:39.360
Because this kind of capacity
to seeing reality out

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:43.100
there toward seeing myself as
part of the problem, of course,

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:47.820
is a key capacity that in
any kind of change process

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:49.120
you want to foster.

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:50.400
You want to develop.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:55.234
So if that happens to a group
moving from here, this mindset,

00:16:55.234 --> 00:16:57.650
which is like a [? deep aid ?]
when you have communication

00:16:57.650 --> 00:17:02.080
in that mindset, and you move
to that style of talking,

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:04.400
that's dialogue.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:08.290
Dialogue is not people
talking with each other.

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:10.630
Dialogue is the
capacity of a system

00:17:10.630 --> 00:17:15.180
to see itself, to reflect
on your own assumption.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:16.747
And yay.

00:17:20.099 --> 00:17:20.740
You did it.

00:17:20.740 --> 00:17:22.030
OK, wonderful.

00:17:22.030 --> 00:17:26.250
So it's not quite synchronized
with what I show here.

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:28.720
But you know, it's
moving in that direction.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:37.760
So making a system see itself
is not only, you could say,

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:39.090
a key feature of dialogue.

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:43.710
It's also 50% of all
change management

00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:49.170
because if I see the system
out there, the problems we face

00:17:49.170 --> 00:17:51.420
is because of all
these idiots around me,

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.500
all the other
departments, and so on.

00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:57.370
And it's only if we
shift the way we talk

00:17:57.370 --> 00:18:01.420
and the mindset that's
underneath to a way

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:03.910
where I am part of
the problem, where

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:08.880
I see how I in my way of framing
as contributing to the problem,

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:12.200
only then when you deal
with multiple stakeholders,

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:15.442
you start to having
useful conversation.

00:18:15.442 --> 00:18:22.390
So in that regard, this
shift, this ego to eco shift,

00:18:22.390 --> 00:18:25.990
really has to do a
lot with this capacity

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:33.000
to bend the beam of observation
back on to the observing self,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.960
back on to making a
group not only sense,

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:40.840
but also see itself as
really the essence you could

00:18:40.840 --> 00:18:44.390
say of systems
thinking and systems

00:18:44.390 --> 00:18:48.750
thinking-based change processes.

00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:51.650
So when we abstract
now from that and say,

00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:54.180
OK, so that's kind
of where you could

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:57.775
say a shift in
consciousness is happening--

00:18:57.775 --> 00:18:59.900
so if you don't like
consciousness, take awareness.

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:04.660
If you don't like awareness,
take mindset, or take the way

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:06.510
we pay attention.

00:19:06.510 --> 00:19:10.470
Paying attention is
essential for all leadership

00:19:10.470 --> 00:19:14.450
because energy
follows attention.

00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:18.610
So wherever you
pay attention to,

00:19:18.610 --> 00:19:21.130
that's where the
energy-- your own,

00:19:21.130 --> 00:19:25.400
but also the energy of the
people around you-- is moving.

00:19:25.400 --> 00:19:27.320
So we know that.

00:19:27.320 --> 00:19:29.240
And what is
essentially meditation?

00:19:29.240 --> 00:19:34.140
It's about paying attention,
about deepening and honing

00:19:34.140 --> 00:19:38.300
our capacity to focus,
to pay attention

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:45.230
in a way that is not
diluted by distraction

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:51.690
by attention deficit
hyperactivity disorder

00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:53.510
kind of symptoms.

