experiment last year.

00:29:05.150 --> 00:29:12.510
This clip basically shows a
little bit the deeper evolution

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:16.630
of learning and action science
space that actually goes back

00:29:16.630 --> 00:29:20.740
to the 1940s and Kurt
Lewin, who actually left

00:29:20.740 --> 00:29:24.550
in the '30s Berlin when
the Nazis took power,

00:29:24.550 --> 00:29:29.210
went to the east coast, and was
the main source of inspiration

00:29:29.210 --> 00:29:32.510
of founding what today
is called action science,

00:29:32.510 --> 00:29:37.230
which is the reason why I left
Germany 20 years ago going

00:29:37.230 --> 00:29:39.570
to the east coast because
I wanted to learn that

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:44.120
methodology which starts with
the sentence that you cannot

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:46.090
understand a system
unless you change it.

00:29:46.090 --> 00:29:48.780
In other words, as
a social scientist,

00:29:48.780 --> 00:29:51.150
you have to engage with.

00:29:51.150 --> 00:29:53.660
You have to participate
in the change processes.

00:29:53.660 --> 00:29:56.690
Otherwise, you're just getting
stuck at the surface data.

00:29:56.690 --> 00:30:01.050
You want to understand the
deep data that's underneath.

00:30:01.050 --> 00:30:07.190
And that lineage, that
also includes the limits

00:30:07.190 --> 00:30:11.010
to growth study
that in the 1970s

00:30:11.010 --> 00:30:14.100
sparked the global
environmental movement.

00:30:14.100 --> 00:30:17.040
And that brings us
now all the way here.

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:21.870
And I think the interesting
thing at the end

00:30:21.870 --> 00:30:24.760
is what we see today
is that we see a deeper

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:28.510
personalization, the deeper
questions of awareness,

00:30:28.510 --> 00:30:35.510
of mindfulness, we see as
very present in society today.

