But most of them were actually
much smaller, so five,

00:32:27.790 --> 00:32:34.030
10, 15, 20, 30 small
groups that came together.

00:32:34.030 --> 00:32:35.740
The second thing
that we learned is

00:32:35.740 --> 00:32:37.620
that institutions--
so that's kind

00:32:37.620 --> 00:32:39.360
of the bottom up grassroots.

00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:42.980
But what was interesting is
that even in the first year,

00:32:42.980 --> 00:32:45.480
we saw several
institutions using

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:49.140
U.Lab as a mobilization tool.

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:53.630
So in this case, Alibaba used
it for their own capacity

00:32:53.630 --> 00:32:57.090
building, leadership
development.

00:32:57.090 --> 00:33:04.180
Then Scotland used it-- the
Scottish government used it

00:33:04.180 --> 00:33:08.350
as a way to reinvent
government from the old model

00:33:08.350 --> 00:33:11.880
that we all know, which
is we create resources

00:33:11.880 --> 00:33:15.440
that we give to our agencies
who deliver services

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:17.390
to beneficiaries.

00:33:17.390 --> 00:33:19.220
The beneficiaries
are frustrated.

00:33:19.220 --> 00:33:22.100
The front line people
who deliver the services

00:33:22.100 --> 00:33:22.890
suffer burnout.

00:33:25.460 --> 00:33:26.870
Now, that's the old model.

00:33:26.870 --> 00:33:30.030
What they now try is
a different model,

00:33:30.030 --> 00:33:32.900
what's called
asset-based, which is

00:33:32.900 --> 00:33:36.030
you use the
resources to activate

00:33:36.030 --> 00:33:40.780
the community themselves to
identify what they will like

00:33:40.780 --> 00:33:44.950
to do, where the real needs
are, and then to co-generate,

00:33:44.950 --> 00:33:47.330
to co-produce these services.

00:33:47.330 --> 00:33:52.850
And they use U.Lab, the
seven-week self-organize

00:33:52.850 --> 00:33:55.210
capacity building around
change initiatives

00:33:55.210 --> 00:33:58.560
that they define as a
mechanism to mobilize.

00:33:58.560 --> 00:34:05.690
So it involved more than
1,000 people last fall.

00:34:05.690 --> 00:34:08.980
And this it is an NGO in China.

00:34:08.980 --> 00:34:12.130
It's the number
one on reinventing

00:34:12.130 --> 00:34:14.429
education in China
that partnered up

00:34:14.429 --> 00:34:15.889
with us a few weeks ago.

00:34:15.889 --> 00:34:19.670
We had a large meeting to
use that U.Lab approach

00:34:19.670 --> 00:34:25.270
to massively bring innovation,
creativity into the education

00:34:25.270 --> 00:34:29.150
system in China by bringing all
the communities, the innovators

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:30.989
of the education
system, together

00:34:30.989 --> 00:34:35.920
and use the MOOC structure
to scale and accelerate

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:39.350
the replication
of what's working.

00:34:39.350 --> 00:34:42.139
Now, the last
thing we learned is

00:34:42.139 --> 00:34:52.940
that you could-- which is
maybe the most interesting--

00:34:52.940 --> 00:34:58.060
that we could engage the global
community of tens of thousands

00:34:58.060 --> 00:35:00.540
of change makers as a whole.

00:35:00.540 --> 00:35:01.800
You see an example here.

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:03.900
So in each, we had
four live sessions.

00:35:03.900 --> 00:35:08.540
In each of them, we use
global moments of stillness,

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:14.900
mindfulness practices, in which
the awareness was not only

00:35:14.900 --> 00:35:21.420
focusing on your own body,
the field around you,

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:26.770
the local group you're
connected with, but also

00:35:26.770 --> 00:35:30.420
the collective body of change
makers around the world,

00:35:30.420 --> 00:35:33.520
across all these hubs that
came together in that moment

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:36.020
and started to interact
with each other, which

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:38.520
was a moment of
transformation and inspiration

00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:41.420
for many as we
learned afterwards.

00:35:41.420 --> 00:35:47.420
So we also engaged
the entire group

00:35:47.420 --> 00:35:50.270
in knowledge creation processes.

00:35:50.270 --> 00:35:52.940
So I'm not going
into details here,

00:35:52.940 --> 00:35:57.080
but it's a one-page summary
of what the U process is,

00:35:57.080 --> 00:35:59.440
which is the four
levels of systems

00:35:59.440 --> 00:36:05.340
change-- micro, individual,
groups, organization system.

00:36:05.340 --> 00:36:10.790
And on this axis, we have
four levels of consciousness

00:36:10.790 --> 00:36:15.760
moving from downloading old
models to deep listening

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:19.520
and transforming
organization, transforming

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:21.830
the way we organize,
transforming

00:36:21.830 --> 00:36:25.500
the way we coordinate,
basically from old style

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:32.260
to our emerging new, and kind
of more horizontal and more

00:36:32.260 --> 00:36:36.780
co-creative in how our
coordination, collaboration

00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:38.080
works.

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:40.540
Now, we asked people,
OK, that's the map.

00:36:40.540 --> 00:36:42.110
Where are you operating today?

00:36:42.110 --> 00:36:43.380
And this is what they set.

00:36:43.380 --> 00:36:46.720
We basically operate on
the first three levels.

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.470
And then we asked,
given the challenges

00:36:49.470 --> 00:36:52.000
that you face on all
these different levels,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.100
where do you need to
operate from in order

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:58.630
to respond to these
challenges appropriately?

00:36:58.630 --> 00:37:01.810
And this is what they said--
it's kind of the [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:01.810 --> 00:37:04.710
When we saw that, we
asked them, wait a minute,

00:37:04.710 --> 00:37:07.760
you just said this is
what you need to do,

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:10.270
this is what you really do.

00:37:10.270 --> 00:37:11.070
Why?

00:37:11.070 --> 00:37:14.520
What's holding you back
today on all these levels

00:37:14.520 --> 00:37:19.930
to actually operate from
this more co-creative space

00:37:19.930 --> 00:37:23.600
of connecting with others and
collaborating with others?

00:37:23.600 --> 00:37:25.100
And here is what they said.

00:37:25.100 --> 00:37:28.660
So we said give us your
response in three words.

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:32.240
And the word cloud that
resulted from that, it basically

00:37:32.240 --> 00:37:38.780
can be summed up with greed,
fear, and ignorance, which

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:45.399
also in Buddhism is known are
known as the three poisons.

00:37:45.399 --> 00:37:47.690
So that was at the beginning
of the seven-week journey.

00:37:47.690 --> 00:37:49.630
At the end of the
seven-week journey,

00:37:49.630 --> 00:37:51.800
we asked them, OK, now
that we have better

00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:53.620
connected with what
you really want

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:58.320
to try to do, with your
life and your work,

00:37:58.320 --> 00:38:02.010
what would it take for
you to actually bring that

00:38:02.010 --> 00:38:04.340
into reality?

00:38:04.340 --> 00:38:08.680
And this is kind
of what they said.

00:38:08.680 --> 00:38:11.820
What I would take is courage.

00:38:11.820 --> 00:38:17.370
And then we asked, OK, and
if you're really committed

00:38:17.370 --> 00:38:19.890
to do that, if you
could mobilize that,

00:38:19.890 --> 00:38:22.880
tap into that courage,
what is the help

00:38:22.880 --> 00:38:25.820
you need from others to succeed?

00:38:25.820 --> 00:38:31.520
And this is what people said--
love, listening, and trust.

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:33.930
So if you step back
and say, OK, what

00:38:33.930 --> 00:38:36.720
is it that we learned from
our global community of change

00:38:36.720 --> 00:38:38.120
makers is what
they really taught

00:38:38.120 --> 00:38:43.680
is this-- that transformation
today happens around--

00:38:43.680 --> 00:38:47.160
or leadership happens around
three transformations, which

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:52.320
is transforming ignorance
to listening and curiosity,

00:38:52.320 --> 00:38:59.890
transforming greed to love
our empathy or compassion,

00:38:59.890 --> 00:39:04.140
and transforming
fear to courage.

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:07.430
So it's these three
transformations

00:39:07.430 --> 00:39:10.820
that we believe-- or that
little community of change

00:39:10.820 --> 00:39:13.250
mirrored back to
us is really what's

00:39:13.250 --> 00:39:17.400
at the heart of the current
leadership challenge

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:20.070
that we face not only
in small pockets,

00:39:20.070 --> 00:39:24.910
but that we face if we start
to address the bigger system

00:39:24.910 --> 00:39:26.320
issues.

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:32.010
In the exit survey,
we learned that those

00:39:32.010 --> 00:39:39.440
that responded, a third of
them said life-changing.

00:39:39.440 --> 00:39:44.130
So how could that
possibly be true?

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:48.640
Well, certainly not
by watching videos.

00:39:48.640 --> 00:39:50.390
You don't have a
life-changing experience.

00:39:50.390 --> 00:39:51.390
I mean, you're attached.

00:39:51.390 --> 00:39:53.410
But it's not a
life-changing experience.

00:39:53.410 --> 00:39:57.090
The only way-- I mean,
this is self-reported,

00:39:57.090 --> 00:40:00.040
of course-- but the only
way that makes sense

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:04.220
is that the main experience
of learning that people had

00:40:04.220 --> 00:40:08.845
was really facilitated at all
the self-organized groups.

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:13.880
And all the
self-organized groups

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:18.240
that met either in
person-- the coaching

00:40:18.240 --> 00:40:22.440
circles, the place-based
groups that even met in person,

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:29.230
or using Google Hangout or other
technologies that made them

00:40:29.230 --> 00:40:33.900
connect virtually which we
enabled through a platform.

00:40:33.900 --> 00:40:37.470
So I started with
the question-- what

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:43.330
does it take to address
some of these processes

00:40:43.330 --> 00:40:44.680
and challenges of disruption?

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:49.450
And what I basically said is
what it takes us two things.

00:40:49.450 --> 00:41:00.470
One is a process, which
is-- OK, interesting.

00:41:00.470 --> 00:41:05.070
So it's a process that
moves through these stages

00:41:05.070 --> 00:41:08.240
of observing, of
connecting to sources

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:11.150
of knowing, and
prototyping, learning

00:41:11.150 --> 00:41:14.200
by doing on the one hand.

00:41:14.200 --> 00:41:17.780
And then the other to
make this process work

00:41:17.780 --> 00:41:21.850
is engaged in this
inner leadership

00:41:21.850 --> 00:41:24.725
work which has to do with
curiosity, compassion,

00:41:24.725 --> 00:41:28.400
and courage, or open mind,
open heart, open will.

00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:31.310
That's basically the
story that I told.

00:41:31.310 --> 00:41:36.180
And I think that what we,
of course, also all see

00:41:36.180 --> 00:41:44.270
is that in reality, often
the opposite is happening.

00:41:44.270 --> 00:41:46.629
So this actually, when
you play it on the Mac,

00:41:46.629 --> 00:41:48.420
it's actually looking
the other way around.

00:41:48.420 --> 00:41:50.390
But never mind.

00:41:50.390 --> 00:41:59.800
So it's the cycle of absencing
that I try to communicate here,

00:41:59.800 --> 00:42:04.410
which is not this
process of opening

00:42:04.410 --> 00:42:05.850
the mind, the heart, the will.

00:42:05.850 --> 00:42:09.650
But it's the opposite,
which is what we see today

00:42:09.650 --> 00:42:13.270
in larger scale
playing out around us

00:42:13.270 --> 00:42:16.370
in corporate politics,
in larger systems.

00:42:16.370 --> 00:42:18.910
In most systems
today, we collectively

00:42:18.910 --> 00:42:21.330
create results
that no one wants.

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:27.940
And so that has to do with
ignorance, greed, and fear, as

00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:30.560
shared before,
which means that we

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:33.740
are moving through a cycle
of denial, de-sensing,

00:42:33.740 --> 00:42:37.250
absencing, disconnecting
with our true purpose,

00:42:37.250 --> 00:42:41.430
and then kind of into a
process of destruction

00:42:41.430 --> 00:42:45.010
as opposed to a
process of co-creation.

00:42:45.010 --> 00:42:53.400
So that's basically, I believe,
the world we are living in

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:58.140
and that we see on the one
hand all of these processes

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:00.790
and networks of innovation.

00:43:00.790 --> 00:43:06.590
On the other hand, we
also see lots of evidence.

00:43:06.590 --> 00:43:09.360
We don't only have to
look to Donald Trump

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:12.370
to see the evidence.

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:17.150
The industry of fear, of
anger, and blaming others,

00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:21.070
and of ignorance really
that is giving rise

00:43:21.070 --> 00:43:26.900
to a lot of phenomena
that suggests

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:30.510
that in the current
evolutionary threshold

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:34.590
we're standing collectively,
we could move backwards very

00:43:34.590 --> 00:43:37.490
easily.

00:43:37.490 --> 00:43:41.280
I think that the interesting
moment we all live in

00:43:41.280 --> 00:43:46.040
is that we actually participate,
or we have the possibility

00:43:46.040 --> 00:43:50.910
to participate, in
that process where

00:43:50.910 --> 00:43:54.180
the mainstream of our
evolution will either

00:43:54.180 --> 00:43:58.350
tap more deeply into
this co-creative space,

00:43:58.350 --> 00:44:02.360
or whether we kind of on a
collective level more and more

00:44:02.360 --> 00:44:06.230
are sucked into this other
space which is really

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:12.930
fueled by the economies and
the industry of ignorance,

00:44:12.930 --> 00:44:16.590
blaming others, and
anger, and fear.

00:44:16.590 --> 00:44:21.480
So that's, I believe,
why the use, the heart

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:25.300
of this challenge has to
do with using technology

00:44:25.300 --> 00:44:29.860
in a new way that is not just
amplifying this stuff here,

00:44:29.860 --> 00:44:34.610
which we see in many all-star
networks going on today,

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:39.710
but that allows us to bring
these types of processes

00:44:39.710 --> 00:44:43.120
here that we all know are
possible, and each of us

00:44:43.120 --> 00:44:46.010
has already participated
in on a smaller scale,

00:44:46.010 --> 00:44:49.400
to bring them to the
level of scale that's

00:44:49.400 --> 00:44:50.990
really necessary today.

00:44:50.990 --> 00:44:57.670
That's what we are passionate--
we'll love to partner deeper

00:44:57.670 --> 00:45:00.890
with what you guys are
doing here in Berlin,

00:45:00.890 --> 00:45:07.560
but also Google in general
in other locations.

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:10.257
And we think that--
my experience

00:45:10.257 --> 00:45:14.420
is-- I mean, my first
Google visit, I remember

00:45:14.420 --> 00:45:16.945
don't do evil or something.

00:45:16.945 --> 00:45:18.320
I don't know
whether that's still

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:19.670
part of corporate culture.

00:45:19.670 --> 00:45:23.260
But I think that there's
always at the heart

00:45:23.260 --> 00:45:25.320
of the new technology
companies, there

00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:28.820
is the aspiration making
the world a better place.

00:45:28.820 --> 00:45:31.250
Yet, that's not
always what happens.

00:45:31.250 --> 00:45:34.970
There's technologies also
used for this stuff here.

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:40.490
So what I would love
to learn from you

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:42.620
is kind of where
you see yourself

00:45:42.620 --> 00:45:47.230
and how we can partner
more deeply to really bring

00:45:47.230 --> 00:45:50.260
these types of new
environments to scale.

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:55.390
Because what we learn is the
openness of people, 75,000

00:45:55.390 --> 00:45:58.260
people, joining up for
the prototype year,

00:45:58.260 --> 00:46:03.720
that's a massive
amount of willingness,

00:46:03.720 --> 00:46:06.430
but also our capacity
to self-organize

00:46:06.430 --> 00:46:11.140
in completely new ways
and use technology

00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:16.790
with more intention to form more
deeper and more dialogue-based

00:46:16.790 --> 00:46:17.500
processes.

00:46:17.500 --> 00:46:21.530
Anyhow, that's what we
are passionate because we

00:46:21.530 --> 00:46:25.820
feel that the
technology-enabling conditions

00:46:25.820 --> 00:46:27.950
that we have formed so
far are very insufficient.

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:30.830
Yet, they worked great.

00:46:30.830 --> 00:46:33.240
But they are still
very insufficient.

00:46:33.240 --> 00:46:37.020
The social media we have
now are mostly downloading,

00:46:37.020 --> 00:46:38.960
kind of broadcasting stuff.

00:46:38.960 --> 00:46:43.310
It's not activating these
deeper innovation processes.

00:46:43.310 --> 00:46:45.137
To do that, we need each other.

00:46:45.137 --> 00:46:46.220
And that's why we're here.

00:46:46.220 --> 00:46:47.320
Thank you.

00:46:47.320 --> 00:46:50.830
[APPLAUSE]

